    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#ferri1923"/>, p. 9, n. <citedRange>8b</citedRange> (no image)</bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>9.139</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>021800</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="divine" ref="#Zeus"><name nymRef="#Ζεύς"><supplied reason="undefined" evidence="previouseditor">Ζ</supplied>η<unclear>ν</unclear><supplied reason="undefined" evidence="previouseditor">ός</supplied></name></persName>.
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
 </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><supplied reason="subaudible">Autel</supplied> de Zeus.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><supplied reason="subaudible">Altar</supplied> of Zeus.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><supplied reason="subaudible">Altare</supplied> di Zeus.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>Simply mentioned by Ferri without illustration or dimensions, this altar might be the one here described.
                    Anyhow, it belongs to the series of altars with compartments of the so-called '<foreign xml:lang="it">agorà degli dei</foreign>'.</p>
	           <p>Only parts of two letters are readable. As they fit the name of Zeus and as the place is the one described by Ferri, C. Dobias-Lalou assumes 
	           that it is the altar mentioned by Ferri.</p>
            </div></body>
